description.text:
First of all, this is still a WIP design and is in its very early stages of design. As you will see, most of the pictures depict a y-axis with only 2 extrusions and one of the pictures depicts a y-axis with 3 extrusions, the dual extrusion design is actually already outdated and the triple extrusion design is the one the files are actually for, all of these images will slowly be replaced and each file will be updated over time before this machine is complete. As of now, I don't recommend building one unless you can design the rest of the machine to suit your own need. The estimated date of completion is not yet known, however, since I am in my final GCSE year and have more important work to take care of, you could expect at least another month before even a slightly working complete model has been released.

I still have many parts to design, so here's a list:

  • y motor mount
  • tidy up z motor mount
  • make x-axis carriers
  • x motor mount
  • x belt tensioner/ end pulley
  • extruder carriage
  • The rest of the brackets holding the machine together (current files are bound to change)
  • internal electrics mount
  • proper side panels (the panels you see in the images are actually just simple mockups,
    roughly like the final design.
  • spool holder
  • and stop mounts

things I may possibly add:

  • quick swap extruder/ tool carriage (the plan is to have a standard carriage which you can't
    remove, but instead, you click or screw in different tools which have adapters to fit the
    carriage. I would want to do this so that I can quickly swap between direct drive and e3d
    type extruders for when I'm printing different types of material)
  • dual extrusion setup (e3d type only, no direct drive dual)
  • hiwin rail axis (not currently planned at all(possibly a v2 of the machine))
  • some neat extruder covers (like the bcn3d extruders)
  • cable management

This is the BOM as of now, this will definitely change as the project continues:
extrusions:

  • 460mm 2020 extrusion (x6)
  • 100mm 2060 extrusion (x2)
  • 380mm 2020 extrusion (x1)
  • 360mm 2020 extrusion (x4)
  • 100mm 2020 extrusion (x9)
  • 180mm 2020 extrusion (x1)
  • 230mm 2020 extrusion (x1)

  • 290mm 2020 extrusion (x1)

      rods:
  • 380mm 8mm hardened steel smooth polished rod (x6)

  • XXXmm 8mm hardened steel smooth polished rod (x2) (this for the x-axis, length
    still unknown)

      printed parts:        (not complete)
  • 380mm rod end (x2)
  • 380mm rod end mirror (x1)
  • 380mm end rear left short (x1)
  • lower extrusion spacer (x2) (bound to change)
  • z axis motor mount nema 17 (x2)
  • centre y bracket (x2)
  • front belt tensoiner bracket (x1)
  • belt pulley carrier tightener (x1)
  • belt tightener screw (x1)
  • screw plate (x1)
  • centre y bracket with cutout (x2)
  • far left short bracket (x2)

that's it for now, for any questions just comment, I'm usually fairly quick to reply if necessary or someone else hasn't already answered your question.

NOTE: for the future, the side panels will all be released in the .dxf format.
NOTE2: don't come asking for the f360 files, I won't give you that much, live with the .st
files.
NOTE3: if you decided to print all of these parts with some others you made yourself, don't
come crying to me if nothing fits. This design is not complete and not tested at all.

NOTE4: (this is for the future) this design is designed to work with the anet a8, in fact, it was
Originally designed to be an upgrade but now that things got out of hand in my
mind, this is a whole new printer. if you do upgrade your a8 to this you will
obviously, need all the extrusions, you will also need a lot of plastic and 2 extra
380mm 8mm dia smooth rods
Since the z-axis uses 4 instead of 2.

NOTE5: (also for the future) Since this isn't necessarily an upgrade anymore but a new
printer, i will eventually also upload files for a 300mm,300mm,400mm(or 300) build
volume (the brackets need to be modified) and a 214mm,214mm,300mm(or 200)
build volume (for mk2a and mk2 beds. Both of these custom build volumes will
include a proper bed suppoert plate in the .dxf format so that you can still use the
normal y-axis rod spacing with a larger bed. This printer is not size customizable
simply by changing extrusion length (except maybe z-axis, but the panels won't fit
then.

petal 1.1 update (1st October):

  • remodelled the z-axis motor mounts
  • began work on the x-axis carriers, files have been uploaded, will be revised
    sooner or later.
  • began a mockup of the extruder as you can see in one of the pictures without the
    side panels on, I'm going for a Bcn3d extruder look.
  • the x axis turns out to be a bit difficult because things looks bigger in CAD than
    they really are :/
    -the distance between the two x rods is only 27mm, yes, 2.7cm, not alot, i think
    the anet a8 has around 40mm between the two rods which means that all anet
    and other i3 printer type extruder mods won't be compatible with this printer. I'll
    probably end up remodelling the whole x axis just for the sake of compatability

The U.K. designed Bristol Fighter was the most successful two-seat combat aircraft of the First World War. title: Flashforge Creator Dual Extruder 3D Printer Leveling Tool

description.text:
First and Foremost, if you are switching between PLA and ABS you need to use this tool and relevel every time. Only if using different temps on the heated bed.This is a simple to use tool that I designed to keep your plate nicely distanced from the extruder. If you like my design(s), feel free to comment on it or leave a donation
Dogecoin Address: DTej2p1x3Dei5jy7VMQbu1abUc9vjTrWgD

Simply find your home axes on the printer.  Now take the printer head and move it to the center of the build plate with your hand.  Take the tool and place it down over one set of bars the carriage is riding on, either the left of the right.  At this point, the two tips sticking down should not touch the build plate. Leave a little distance between the build plate and the tool.  Adjust the screws on the bottom of the build plate until the distances between the tool tips and the build plate are even and the extruder is not touching.  Now move it to the opposite side and do the same thing. Just make sure the build plate is the same distance to each point on the tool in each position.  It's a little better if you sand the part to nice square finishes for better alignment.

Wanted to make a mechanical slide that didnât cost hundreds of dollars! HA! Anyway, I think this is a pretty simple design; mainly made from 3D Printed Parts. Not the quality of an OEM Slide but works none the less. Other than some screws and nuts, has two main OEM items to purchase. One, 1/8â Brass U-Channel. Itâs pretty cheap and you can get it at most any Hobby Store or online. Two, need 1/8â diameter steel balls. I got mine online but should be easy to get.
Other than that, this was easy to put together. Assemble the unit on its side; use posted pictures with assembly notes. Things to note.
  • When building the parts pay attention to build direction. I needed no supports for any of the parts. Think it took about an hour and a half to print a set of parts on standard settings.
  • The Brass Channel isnât perfect. I found one side of the U-Shape to be slightly higher than the other. I just made sure to keep this bias to one side of the bearings. If you machined your own U-Channel you could improve performance.
  • After assembly there is still some play (.005-.010). But, with a modest load (couple of pounds or less) this slide will give consistent use and good life. Interested to see if someone can give it some practical use.
  • I provided Bearing Cage files for 2, 3, 4, 5 balls so you can play with how many balls you want vs. application.
    • Note: some of the parts (blue) are not shown in the correct orientation. The Slide Base and Slide Body are shown upside down and the Slide Base Rail is shown on it's end. Should be on the long side so the long pocket faces up.

description.text:
The Wise Planter is a post-smart planter. No gadgets, no sensors, no batteries. Basic physics lets you visually assess the needs of your favorite desktop plants.

Update! 12/15/17 In celebration of being featured as 3D Printing Today's thing of the week I've uploaded the Voronoi Base! It can be swapped out with the Wave Base to offer that extra-special 3D print-y geometry. Check out the 3D Printing Today podcast!

The inner pot sits on a spring which rests against the outer base. As the soil loses moisture, the pot slowly rises while the base remains in place. Eventually an adjustable indicator ring is revealed to remind you to water.

The inner pot is a little over 4"x4"x3.5" (LxWxH). The planter total is 4.75"x4.75"x6" at maximum height. You can print all parts in PLA, PET, ABS -- pick your favorite rigid polymer!

If you'd like to learn more about the design process used, I blogged about it extensively! Start with the first post, here.

I designed for (and use) Century Spring #12420, but you have to order a $50 minimum! Challenge to you all -- please find a spring readily available that works!! Click here for the 12420 product page. The 12420 is perfect, but a little stiffer would work, too. I'm working on finding a more available spring, but I got sick of waiting to get the design perfect before I published it. :-) Moonshot -- print a spring!

Step 1 -- Remove from bed, test fits, and coat if desired

Once printed, put everything together. Does the pot slide up and down in the base with little resistance? Is the band tight on the pot but loose enough for you to adjust it?

You can also coat the bottom of the base to prevent water egress. Wax, plast-i-dip, conformal coating, epoxy. You pick!

Step 2 -- Add a plant!

If the parts go together well, fill the pot with soil and put a plant in it! I like to sift the potting soil at first to catch little bits of pumice/rock in the drain holes. This approach minimizes weight -- if you add a layer of stones/gravel, you risk adding too much weight. Once you plant the plant -- DON'T water it!

I like to sift a bit of potting soil to get a thin layer of chunks at the bottom. Step 3 -- Adjust indicator band

You should have a dry plant. Adjust the indicator so that it is clearly visible. This is probably dryer than you want your plant to get in the future.

Step 4 -- Water, wait, repeat

Water your plant and watch it settle. Pour out excess. Now over the days to come watch as it rises slowly! Monitor your soil moisture carefully for the early weeks to get the indicator set properly.

The mechanical design process...

I blogged extensively about the design process behind this product. Check it out on my website! www.openfabpdx.com/blog

I also made the wheel bearing distance 0.5mm tighter than supposed to be extra certain, so assemble with eccentric nuts all the way out. I used a pen to mark which side is furthest away.
Also check your eccentric nuts, many of what creality supplies is not very eccentric at all.

This is based on the original measurements then small changes.

Two versions:
Skookumified: slightly too large, you need to slightly re-adjust the microswitch level for X end stop to work because the belt's crimp will touch the belt pulley. This is what i use myself.

More skookum: Slightly changed dimensions so no need to microswitch changes, few mm smaller, few mm different position for the belt pulleys. This is to be considered V2 but is untested so far.

PLEASE NOTE that i did not fix the geometry issues on these versions yet. The front side pulleys are not aligned with the carriage.

Uses original hardware. I do recommend adding a few washers on top side tho.

ALSO NOTE Ender-4 is NOT Core-XY but H-Bot. This will not completely solve the racking issue, i was hoping the guides would be enough, but ABS is too soft of an material.

This is Talhakimt I modelled then lost the Solidworks file. If you're finding this you probably know what it is.  
Anyways, Here is the STL file for now until I remodel it from scratch.

This is an easy-to-print chainguard for a chainring that does not accept a guard. I have no idea what brand the chainring is, but it has 48 teeth.
I guess you can use it on smaller chainrings as well, it's meant to be fastened with zip-ties.

Instructions:
Printed in PLA at 205C, 20% infill. Print with the flat side down for a nice adhesion, drafted side down for easy removal. It requires a minimum of 200mm x 100mm printing surface. You would probably need to print two copies. No supports, rafts are optional.

Features:

  • Fits an i3 / Makerbot or similar printing bed since it requires about 20x10cm.
  • Ugly, but uses a minimum of material to get the job done.
  • "Fast" to print, should take less than one hour.
  • The drafted/chamfered (narrow side) should sit on the chain side so it allows the chain to clear.
  • The outside corners are rounded so your pants have a chance to clear the guard and chain.
  • Crankshaft clearance is 33mm from center, outside diameter is 210mm.
  • Tested!
  • You can clone it and modify it to make it your own just by editing an OnShape sketch: https://cad.onshape.com/documents/41ae2ad591eadd1abd046603/w/e04e9aa26154bb40d38aec2f/e/2b6c9f6084c98b69cb31430b

Post-printing:
In the case of this chainguard no modifications were needed. However, I designed my other chainguards flat and used a lighter (blue part of the flame) to soften them and form them by hand so they sit proud (outside of the chain). If you find your version sits too close to the chainring, you can do that as well, it takes 2 minutes.

Zu beachten ist, das man zusätzlich verstellbare Füße verbauen sollte, damit das Netzteil noch genug Abstand zur Aufstellfläche hat. Auf den Bildern sind meine verstellbaren Füße zusehen. Ich werde diese bei Bedarf später noch hochladen.

Die orginal Schrauben, die den Deckel mit dem Gehäuse verbinden, habe ich durch M3x8 bzw. M3x10, und jeweils noch eine Unterlegscheibe, ersetzt. Zu sehen ist das auf dem 2. und 4. Bild. Es ist bei allen Schrauben darauf zu achten, daß keine Schraube zu weit in das Gehäuse reinragt.

Als Lüfter habe ich einen 80x80x10mm / 24V / 2Pin verbaut, es sollte aber auch ein Lüfter mit 15mm Bauhöhe reinpassen, aber zur Sicherheit vorher nochmal prüfen.

Wer später dann doch wieder einen 60mm Lüfter einbauen will, kann sich dann die 60mm Aufnahme ausdrucken, die hat die gleichen Außenmaße wie die 80mm Aufnahme, nur eben für einen 60mm Lüfter.

Auf YouTube hat Pitsch3D ein Video dazu gemacht, das solltest du dir auf alle Fälle mit ansehen.

title: 4 Way Wet Diverter for Aquaponics or Hydroponics

description.text:
This is a Diverter or Indexing head for Hydroponics or Aquaponics. This is a wet and low pressure diverter designed for 1" PVC pipe fixtures. My intention for the diverter is to have a single circulation pump which returns to the tank. Overflow from the tank is gravity fed to the diverter, then to 4 grow beds. I'll be using a 1" high flow pump for my setup, so I'll have two overflows which feed beds along with an emergency overflow in case the system backs up. The rod is connected to a stepper motor with a coupler. The stepper is driven by Arduino connected to water level sensors in each of the grow beds. When a sensor is triggered (indicating a full tub), the stepper is driven to the next index. On the coupler is a epoxied magnet, with a magnetic sensor to detect location. Code to drive the diverter is located here:
https://github.com/ooeygui/aquaponics/blob/master/Diverter/Diverter.ino NOTE: Requires MCAD scad extension, as well as included external files. Update 3/17
Added an indexing plate and a model of a roller switch. Next change will be to make the drive axle coupler and mount for the roller switch. I'm going to punch a hole through the riser so that the motor can be pipe clamped to the PVC feed pipe. Update: 11/28:
Massive refactor. Downsized the stepper to a Nema17. Integrated the stepper motor mount into the inlet. The diverter cap is now bolted to the bell.

title: Dual Cooling 40mm Fan Attachment for Kossel Mini

description.text:
This is my first design using DesignSpark Mechanical - a free cad program that I recommend for beginners. It is a 40 mm fan attachment for Kossel Mini with J-Head Hot-end. I split the airflow in half, the top parts cools the PEEK of the hot-end and the bottom half flows in two channels around the tip of the hot-end and is directed at the printing nozzle.
The attachment also contains the attachment piece for the J-Head to the Kossel Mini effector and uses three 3mm screws.
The fan is attached using self taping screws directly into the plastic. (I printed in PLA). The attachment has four 2 mm holes that can be enlarged if needed.
I also added the DesignSparkMechanichal source file (.rsdoc) if it helps.

Assembly Note:
Attach first the J-Head to the attachment top. It should have the rectangle part centered in the space between the two air evacuation areas. My heating cartridge was not centered and I had to rotate the head.

comments.text: I've edited the design and shortened the bottom by 3mm so that the MK V hotend protrudes below the bottom of the shroud. See the Remixes button on the right, or the link below.

remixed_from.author: janrm
remixed_from.title: Mazzer burrs on Kitchenaid grinder adapter plate

description.text:
This thing is sort of a work in progress, as I've been adjusting files here and there after printing the parts and improving upon the design.

I wanted to upgrade my Kitchenaid Proline Burr grinder, but like many, couldn't get ahold of Ben Choong's mod kit. I eventually stumbled upon janrm's 3d files. Since janrm didn't have a a drill template like Ben's mod, I made one using janrm's files.

Since it's probably not a great idea to use plastic for the back burr adapter like the aluminum one Ben uses, I decided to drill directly into the body of the grinder and use a plastic adapter that doesn't require heavy structural integrity. Also, I found I needed an adapter despite reading in forums that other people just attached the burr directly to the body of the grinder. The mazzer burrs are at least a millimeter larger in diameter compared to the stock burrs. They won’t fit into the little round cavity that’s in the back of the grinder.
I've edited the adapter plate so there's a hole at the top. The grinder seems to work better with all screws screwed in. Since the third hole isn't aligned with a hole in the body of the grinder, fix the screw with a nut on the other end. Then attach the burr with the adapter to the body of the grinder.

I think the mazzer mini burrs use m5 machine screws. I couldn't find any that fit the burr nicely at my local hardware stores, so I used 8-32 screws. I think 8-32 is a bit smaller than m5, but the drill templates should work for either. If you print in plastic, you can just drill right through it easily.

Also, this mod creates a lot of grind retention in the grinder. More so than using the stock burrs. So I made some washers that fit behind the stationary back burr. I made a 2 mm thick washer, and a 1 mm thick washer. Depending on how fine you plan to grind, you can use one or the other, or stack them and use both.

I suggest watching Ben Choong's video before attempting this mod. It really helped me out on what parts were needed.

Lastly, try to print these files in white, so that if any of the parts start breaking apart, you can more easily see it in the grinds. The only part I would not print in white is the adjuster spacer, I would print that in black to preserve the aesthetic of the grinder.

title: Tabletop Industrial Terrain CNC/Laser Cut

description.text:
I am in the process of trying to figure out how to easily open source this project if there is interest. If you have suggestions or information that can help me do this, let me know!

This is a set of industrial tabletop wargamming terrain that can be cut out using a CNC or laser cutter. I use it for Shadow War Armageddon terrain.

I cut these out using a Mostly Printed CNC (MPCNC) and 3mm hardboard from Home Depot since I couldn't find 3mm MDF in my local stores. The hardboard is not very rigid so they are a little wobbly but completely usable. MDF should be much more stable.

description.text:
After noticing that all of my LiPos were more beat up on the bottom than they were on the top, I set off on a mission to design something that would stop the LiPo abuse! 1300mah 4s(and 3s) LiPos aren't cheap so you want them to last as long as possible especially if you're on a tight budget like I am. That means adequately protecting them during crashes. The LiPo battery pad I designed functions similar to the gel pads that many people use as it simply elevates the battery above the bolts which will dent it upon impact. Unlike other gel pads though, this one is specially designed for the ZMR250 and simply snaps into the top plate! The upper pad functions to protect the battery in the event of an upside down crash, scrape of a tree branch. It also has triangular shock absorbing protrusions at the front and back which protect the upper edges of the battery which are also parts that often get damaged in a crash. Lastly, the upper pad increases the surface area of the lipo strap ensuring that it doesn't fly off during a crash or in flight.

title: Crafting Table Box with Sliding Lid

description.text:
A box with a sliding lid, designed to look like a crafting table from Minecraft.

This is not an official Minecraft product. This model is designed to resemble a game asset, but was not extracted from a game asset. I believe that I am following Mojang's Minecraft Brand and Asset Guidelines by releasing this fan art object under a non-commercial license.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Infill:

20% / 100%

Notes:

Supports Not Required
No supports are required for either part, whether you are using a single or dual extruder. The overhangs on the edges are all no more than 0.5mm, which is small enough that most printers should have no trouble. The grooves for the lid have a 45 degree overhang, which should print fine.

You will need good bed adhesion, otherwise the parts will not fit together properly. A heated print bed is recommended. If you do not have one, use your favourite method for ensuring that your print sticks to the bed (a wide brim may help), and monitor the print for the first several layers.

Single Extruder
Print crafting_table_box-single.stl and crafting_table_box-lid.stl. The infill setting doesn't matter much, although you should use at least a bit of infill (20% works well) to give the walls some strength.

Dual Extruder
Combine the crafting_table_box-wood.stl and crafting_table_box-metal.stl files for a two-tone print. The lid (crafting_table_box-lid.stl) is only one material. Print the "metal" part solid (100% infill). The "wood" part should have some infill (20%) to give the walls some strength.

In a two-material print, the "metal" parts of the design are a collection of small pieces. Many printers have a hard time printing shapes this small. For best results, slow both the print and travel speeds and accelerations way down. Not much of the "metal" material is used, so this won't have a huge impact on your total print time, but it will improve your results.

For the photos shown above, I used the instructions below to enlarge the box to 6cm and printed it at 0.1mm layer resolution using these settings:

  • FibreForce Wood Infused PLA: (default PLA values)
    • print speed: 70 mm/s
    • travel speed: 250 mm/s
    • print acceleration: 4000 mm/s2
    • travel acceleration: 5000 mm/s2
  • Ultimaker Silver Metallic PLA:
    • print speed: 30 mm/s
    • travel speed: 70 mm/s
    • print acceleration: 140 mm/s2
    • travel acceleration: 210 mm/s2

The reason for turning down the travel speed is to prevent hot filament in the nozzle from tugging on the still-warm material just laid down as it moves away. If you don't do this, you are likely to get blobs at the bottom and edges of the metal parts, which you will need to file off.
If you find the lid is too tight, just shave down the edges of the lid slightly with sandpaper or a sharp knife. Or, use the instructions below to generate your own box with a larger tolerance.

Summary

I drew vector graphics in Inkscape, exported them to EPS files, then used pstoedit to convert those to OpenSCAD-compatible DXF files. An OpenSCAD script loads and extrudes the various vector components, creating a cube that looks like a crafting table. Finally, another OpenSCAD script turns the cube into a box with a sliding lid.

Details

I have obviously used a Minecraft crafting table for inspiration. Minecraft block textures are 16x16 pixels, so I started off with a 16x16mm grid. In Inkscape, I drew the sides and top of the crafting table. I tried to interpret what the pixelated game textures were trying to represent: a saw, an axe, and snips. The results are "front.svg", "side.svg", and "top.svg".

Next, I split each of the initial SVG files into separate files based on the depth to which each part should be etched. While Inkscape can export DXF files, the files it writes use features not supported by OpenSCAD. Instead, I exported the SVG files to EPS, then used "pstoedit" to convert those to OpenSCAD-compatible DXF files. If you're on Linux (or another Unix-like OS) and have both Inkscape and pstoedit installed, there's a Makefile that will convert all the SVGs to DXFs at once. "pstoedit" is used like this:
pstoedit -dt -f "dxf_s: -mm -splineaspolyline -splineprecision 100" filename.eps filename.dxf

The "crafting_table.scad" script loads all the DXF files and assembles them into a crafting table. If you run this script directly, you will get a solid crafting table (i.e. a block, not a box). The "material" variable near the top determines what part gets generated.

The "crafting_table_box.scad" script uses "boxify_slide.scad" to turn the crafting table into a box with a lid. The "part" and "material" variables determine what part gets generated. The variables below that control the size of the box.

This design does not work with the Thingiverse Customizer because it relies on a bunch of DXF files. Just scaling the models up or down may not work very well, because the tolerances on the lid will change.

But fear not! It's not difficult to change the size yourself.

Download Sources

Download and install OpenSCAD. You only need OpenSCAD. You do not need any of the other programs I used to create this.

Also download and unpack sources.zip. You can unpack it anywhere you like, but all of the DXF and SCAD files must be together in one directory.

Edit the Size

To change the size of the box, launch OpenSCAD and open "crafting_table_box.scad".
Modify the variables at the top of the file according to the directions below.

Here are the most important variables you will want to change:

  • box_width is the size of the box.
  • tolerance is the total clearance between the lid and the groves. If you find the lid does not fit in the groves, increase this.
Render to STL

The lid and each box material are rendered as a separate file. Edit the "part" and "material" variables to determine what gets rendered:

  • part: valid values are "lid" or "box".
  • material: valid values are "wood", "metal", or "single" (for a single extruder)

In OpenSCAD, click Design > Render (or press F6) and wait for the display to be updated. Then click File > Export > Export as STL.

Repeat for each box material and for the lid.

"boxify_slide.scad" (inside "sources.zip") is an OpenSCAD script that can convert any cube-like object into a box with a sliding lid. I have released that file (and only that file) under the BSD 3-clause license. That means you can use "boxify_slide.scad" in your own projects, even for a commercial use.

I consider "boxify_slide.scad" to be alpha quality. Once I have improved it, I plan to publish it as a separate Thing for your convenience.

description.text: Another version of a bic pen...
support pour lcd AM8

Whats this?

A 360 degree turnable air inlet, so you can deside if you want the cooler air from above, or the warmer air coming from the bed below running true your cooling system.

Why?

  • reduces fan noise.
  • keeps particals out of your fan.
  • sucks only the air from where you want it to the cooler (can rotate 360 degrees)
  • Adds a new variable for tuning your setup. (controle freaks love this one)
  • Industrial look just looks awsome on your Anet printer :P

How come you made this?

Since the smallest things can have impact on your prints, and everybody tweaking all those aspects, I was kind of surprised to only see (a lot) of nozzles for the cooling part of the printer, and no tweaks to make the air intake more efficient.
So i came up with this Industrial looking, 360 degree turnable Air inlet.

Out of the box the cool fan would suck random air into the cooling system from all around him, including the hot air coming straight from the bed, thus making the air to cool with warm.....ehm...that sounds a bit like it needs a tweak :P
I figured if i could make a air inlet that i could turn away from the heatbed, i will suck in more 'cooler' air, and do a overall better job in cooling.(slightly)

When designing the inlet I thought it would maybe be usefull if you could adjust the intake so you could suck in the warm air from the heat bed to mayby aid in printing and cooling some filaments who are more hungry for temp, and need a slower/diffirent cooling process.

Does this effect my general airflow?

I roughly calculated the open space that the fan has to suck in the air,
and made sure there is at least that amount of space in the Inlet also.
Theoretically you should not have any drop in flow.
I did not notice any myself when testing.
(absolutly no rocket science here, more uhm..wet finger sience :P)

Did it Improve your prints?

Only used it with Pla filaments so far (a few small prints) the only thing that I noticed is less stringing. So it does work as intended I geuss, then again, its hard to say its purely cause of the intake, but i did took notice of it without changing any other thing.
More so the used Cooling nozzle probably also has great impact on the cooling in general, and on the effect rate of the inlet as well.

Stringing has little to no impact on the direct print quality.
So as for the question:Does it improve my prints?
I have to say for now: Not Noticible with PLA.
I did notice a not intended reduction of the fans noise though,
more on the lower speeds, wich is a great bonus!
Further testing to be done.

Isn't this going to be flimsy and floppy?

Nope, its nice and tight :P

When printing do I need support?

For the base you dont, just print as is.
For the inlet I did use support, think you should to.
Just dont use a Brim, you have enough cleaning to do allready,
this will make it even wors (believe me :P)

Installation:

  • It's a tight tight fit! On purpose!
  • After printing make sure to clean your prints very good.
    Specially the inside of the ring on the Base and the bottom part of the Inlet. (where they
    snap together)
  • Now even when cleaned nicely, its pretty hard to make the parts Click together.
    (take notice of the tiny guide rail in the base, and guides on the bottom of the Inlet)
    Use hot water/steam (carefull) to make the ring a TINY bit softer so you can push the
    parts together more easily. (pushing on the two screw holes gently opens it up)
  • When letting it cool down from fitting it, place it on a flat surface and turn the Inlet around
    in the base a few times , this should not go to easy, and should go with a rough 'clicking
    motion'.
  • The mount posts for the 2 screws I on purpose made a bit higher,
    its easyer to take some off, then add some to it , just use the blue pliers from the anet to
    trim them down if needed. I used the M3x20 screws, and took off 1mm from the posts.
  • Now Install it nice and tight over your Cooling Fan and you are done.
    If all went as planned you can now turn your intake to the direction you want,
    (with a bit force), and enjoy your new variable and Industrial Look :D

Let me know your Expirience and findings with the Inlet!

If you like my design, please think about a small donation for a nice hot coffee,
and for further development as well! Thanks!

Hope you Enjoy,
Keep creating!
